node.text: Sharing in partnership with @balmuda_usa my version of #ABetterMorning - one that leans on simple routine. To wake early, draw a warm bath, sip hot water with lemon & enjoy a slice of sourdough toast before the rest of the house awakes and the chaos of these unstrung summer days engulfs me. A single hour to myself that helps keep me steady. #sponsored #BALMUDAthetoaster

node.text: Like a lot of you here I’ve spent the past week dedicated to deep self reflection. Getting comfortable with being uncomfortable. Listening, learning, drafting the words for pieces to a conversation I hope to have here soon, but for now I wanted to share a song, a piece of my heart and changed me forever. One I heard as a little girl back when my mother played the album non stop in ‘88. I remember how it split me open in ways I had never experienced. Taught me about race injustice, poverty, abuse and introduced the narrative of those on the outer fringes of the American Dream. I remember crying the first time I heard her sing It, and every single time thereafter. Back then I was a child rooting for the black woman driving that car and now a grown woman rooting for her sons and daughters who’ve taken the wheel. A song I come back to again and again. That never stops breaking me open in real & beautiful ways. Figured we could listen together here on a Saturday afternoon headed for change.

node.text:
Three days later it’s still a solid shock to me, how after months of countless hours spent researching a story I fell into and couldn’t shake (like I’ve been known to do since as long as I can remember) I ended up one of a select few inside that courthouse hearing Wednesday afternoon. Processing (in real time) the worlds biggest pop star pleading for her life. 

I won’t forget our scattered actions trying to find enough pens and note pads upon learning we were in, or the chill that came attached to a long silent pause at roll call that dissolved as soon as her voice (one familiar to us all) introduced herself as “Britney Jean Spears.” 

Two and a half hours of growling  accusations aimed at family members on call, exposing to a room full of strangers her personal medical records, everything she’s been denied, the extent of neglect, the abuse she’s endured, the anger she carries and the freedom she craves.

As much as I kept thinking what an anomaly this was. For Me, a mother from Orange County armed simply  with an insatiable desire to unearth  truths at the center of these tales, landed at the center of a story the whole world is watching. One I set out to investigate on my own accord but eventually invited an entire army by sharing the process instead of dissecting internally. Like I’ve done now by habit my whole life.

There was a moment of clarity near the end. Where the notion of happenstance started to slip away and I felt for that moment in time I was exactly where I should be.

Because I raise my boys to honor their gifts. To peruse what they love and are gifted at. To show them you can indeed make a living chasing that which you love. But I suppose inside those lessons I’m handing out and preaching, I’m still learning too. #freebritney
